<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="19" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/0028825X.2005.9512985" author="Johnston, PR" journalOrPublisher="New Zealand Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" pagination="679 - 719" refId="B8" refString="Johnston, PR, Park, D, 2005. Chlorociboria (Fungi, Helotiales) in New Zealand. New Zealand Journal of Botany 43: 679 - 719, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/0028825X.2005.9512985" title="Chlorociboria (Fungi, Helotiales) in New Zealand." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/0028825X.2005.9512985" volume="43" year="2005">Johnston and Park (2005</bibRefCitation>
: 690-693) provided a description of 
<taxonomicName class="Leotiomycetes" family="Cyttariaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="C. novae-zelandiae" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="novae-zelandiae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">C. novae-zelandiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from New Zealand specimens reported under the name 
<taxonomicName class="Leotiomycetes" family="Cyttariaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="C. argentinensis" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="argentinensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">C. argentinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Subsequent DNA sequencing of specimens from Argentina identified as 
<taxonomicName class="Leotiomycetes" family="Cyttariaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="C. argentinensis" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="argentinensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">C. argentinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, showed that the New Zealand species is phylogenetically distinct. Morphologically, the two species are similar, both with an excipulum comprising highly gelatinous 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">textura intricata</emphasis>
, the apothecia lacking hair-like tomentum hyphae, and with small, allantoid ascospores. The New Zealand species has somewhat smaller ascospores (average 7.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
versus 9.9 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.9 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
) and narrower asci (3.5-4.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
versus 4-5.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
) compared with the Argentinian specimens recognised here as 
<taxonomicName class="Leotiomycetes" family="Cyttariaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="C. argentinensis" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="argentinensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">C. argentinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The Argentinian specimens match closely the description of 
<bibRefCitation author="Dixon, JR" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" pagination="193 - 237" refId="B3" refString="Dixon, JR, 1975. Chlorosplenium and its segregates. II. The genera Chlorociboria and Chlorencoelia. Mycotaxon 1: 193 - 237" title="Chlorosplenium and its segregates. II. The genera Chlorociboria and Chlorencoelia." volume="1" year="1975">Dixon (1975)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
